sif3.common.model
Class QueryMetadata

java.lang.Object
  sif3.common.model.QueryMetadata
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable
public class QueryMetadata
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable

Utility class used by the provider to extract URL parameters relating to paging information, query informatione etc. In essence this class helps extracting and adding URL query parameters (everything after the '?' in a URL).

Author:
Joerg Huber

setValues

public void setValues(java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> attributeValueMap)
This method sets all the properties in this class for which a value is found in the given attributeValueMap. Only properties for which a value is found are set. All other properties remain untouched. Note that only properties for which there is a TAG constant defined at the top of this class will be considered. If the Map is null then no action is taken.

Parameters:
attributeValueMap - The attribute (key) - value map from which the properties of this object shall be set.

setValues

public void setValues(javax.ws.rs.core.MultivaluedMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> attributeValueMap)
This method behaves exactly the same as setValues(Map) above except the Map here is a MultivaluedMap that is used in REST URI paramters. It is a pure convenience method.

Parameters:
attributeValueMap -

getQueryParameters

public java.util.Map<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> getQueryParameters()
Returns a hash map of all values in this class that are NOT NULL. The key values of the hash map are the parameter names and the values in the hash map are the values of the parameter. If no values are set in this class then an empty hash map is returned.

This is a pure convenience method.

Example:

HashMap[page]: 2

HashMap[pageSize]: 10

Returns:
See desc.

getQueryParametersAsMultivaluedMap

public javax.ws.rs.core.MultivaluedMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.String> getQueryParametersAsMultivaluedMap()
This method behaves the same as getQueryParameters() but instead of a Map it returns a MultivaluedMap that is more user-friendly when it comes to REST URIs and parameters. All other assumptions and constraints are the same as in getQueryParameters().

This is a pure convenience method.

Returns:
See desc of getQueryParameters().
